      "Herod Agrippa II is the man who almost believed, or at least said something that sounds like he almost did. When Paul delivered his defense before Agrippa and the Roman governor Festus, the account climaxes with one of the most debated lines in Acts. Paul asks Agrippa directly: \"King Agrippa, do you believe the prophets? I know that you believe.\" Agrippa's reply — traditionally rendered \"Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian\" — has been translated in various ways, from a sincere near-conversion to a dismissive joke. The ambiguity might be the point.\n\nAgrippa II was the last king in the Herodian line, and he knew it. He ruled minor territories in northern Palestine at the pleasure of Rome, and his power was real but circumscribed. He had Jewish heritage and enough theological education to follow Paul's arguments — Paul explicitly acknowledged this — but he also had a Roman patron to keep happy and a reputation to maintain. Believing Paul would have cost him everything institutional in his life.\n\nThe hearing itself was more spectacle than legal proceeding. Festus had inherited Paul's case from Felix and couldn't figure out what charges to send to Caesar, so he brought in Agrippa for a consultation. Agrippa and his sister Bernice arrived \"with great pomp\" — Luke uses the Greek word phantasia, which is as sarcastic as it sounds. They sat in a ceremonial hall while a chained prisoner explained the resurrection to them. Festus interrupted to call Paul insane. Agrippa gave his famous half-answer. And Paul went to Rome anyway.\n\nAgrippa II lived on for decades, siding with Rome during the Jewish revolt of 66-70 AD, watching the temple his ancestors had rebuilt get destroyed, and dying as the final chapter of a dynasty that had been entangled with salvation history for over a century. He had heard the gospel from its greatest advocate, in person, with full understanding of its Jewish roots. And he walked away.",
