    bioFull:
      "Festus walked into a mess he didn't create. He replaced Felix as governor of Judea and immediately inherited a prisoner named Paul who had been languishing in custody for two years with no resolution. The Jewish leaders wanted Paul dead. Paul was a Roman citizen who had appealed to Caesar. Festus was a bureaucrat trying to figure out what to write in the cover letter.\n\nHis frustration is almost sympathetic. He told Agrippa plainly that the charges against Paul weren't what he expected — no accusations of sedition or violence, just disputes about \"their own religion and about a certain Jesus, who was dead, but whom Paul asserted to be alive.\" Festus was a Roman administrator confronting a theological argument he had no framework for evaluating. He needed a crime, and all he had was a resurrection claim.\n\nThe hearing before Agrippa was Festus's attempt to solve a procedural problem. He couldn't send a prisoner to Caesar without specifying the charges, and he didn't understand the charges. When Paul got to the part about the resurrection, Festus interrupted with a shout: \"Paul, you are out of your mind! Your great learning is driving you insane!\" It's the reaction of a practical man confronting a category he can't file. Festus wasn't hostile to Paul personally — he just lived in a world where dead people stay dead, and anyone who argued otherwise needed a doctor.\n\nFestus died in office around 62 AD, only a couple of years into his tenure. He was, by most accounts, a more competent and honest administrator than Felix. He simply didn't know what to do with a prisoner whose offense was believing something impossible.",
