      "Felix is the man who understood just enough to be afraid and not enough to change. When Paul stood before him and spoke about righteousness, self-control, and the coming judgment, Luke records that Felix was alarmed. That's a specific word — not bored, not dismissive, but genuinely unsettled. He sent Paul away with the promise to call for him later at a \"convenient time.\" The convenient time never came.\n\nHis background explains part of the dynamic. Felix was a freed slave who rose to extraordinary power — a rarity in the Roman world that made him both ambitious and insecure. The historian Tacitus wrote that he \"exercised the power of a king with the mind of a slave,\" which is devastating but illuminating. He married Drusilla, a Jewish princess, which gave him some exposure to Jewish religion and made Paul's message about judgment land differently than it might have for a typical Roman.\n\nFelix kept Paul in prison for two years, calling for him frequently for private conversations. Luke says plainly that he was hoping Paul would offer him a bribe. The picture that emerges is pathetic in the original sense: a man drawn back to conversations that disturbed him, unable to act on what he heard, hoping the prisoner might solve his problem with money instead of truth. He had access to the greatest theological mind of his generation, and he turned it into a shakedown.\n\nWhen Felix was recalled from office and replaced by Festus, he left Paul in prison as a political favor to the Jewish leaders. His final act in the narrative was using an innocent man as a bargaining chip. Felix didn't reject the gospel with a dramatic gesture — he let it sit in a holding cell until someone else had to deal with it.",
