    bioFull:
      "Bernice appears in Acts seated next to her brother Agrippa II as Paul delivers his defense, and Luke introduces their entrance with a Greek word — phantasia — that drips with irony. Great pomp. Great spectacle. These two representatives of a dying dynasty arrived in full ceremonial display to hear a prisoner in chains explain the resurrection. The contrast between their trappings and Paul's condition is the scene's entire visual argument.\n\nShe was the great-granddaughter of Herod the Great, daughter of Herod Agrippa I (who had killed James and been struck down by an angel), and sister of Agrippa II. Roman gossip, recorded by historians like Juvenal and Josephus, alleged an incestuous relationship with her brother — a rumor that followed her throughout her life. Whether true or not, it shaped her public reputation and limited her options in a world that used women's sexual conduct as political currency.\n\nBernice's life was a series of strategic marriages and alliances. She married twice, briefly lived with a third husband, and later became the mistress of the Roman general Titus — the same Titus who would destroy the Jerusalem temple in 70 AD. She was a survivor in a family where survival was the exception, and she navigated Roman power politics with more skill than most of her male relatives.\n\nIn Paul's hearing, she is silent. Luke records no reaction from her — no fear like Felix, no near-persuasion like Agrippa, no exasperation like Festus. She heard the gospel from its most articulate defender and left no recorded response. She is the audience member who came for the show and left without a review.",
