    faithJourney:
      "Bernice's faith journey, if she had one, is invisible in the text. She sat in the room where Paul laid out the gospel with maximum rhetorical force, and Luke doesn't give her a single word in response. That silence might reflect the limits of Luke's access, or it might be the point. Some people encounter the truth and it passes through them like light through glass — present, visible, but leaving no mark.\n\nWhat we can say is that Bernice grew up inside a family that had been colliding with God's purposes for four generations. Her great-grandfather tried to kill the Messiah. Her father killed an apostle and was struck dead. Her brother heard the gospel and deflected. She heard it and said nothing. The Herodian pattern wasn't outright rejection — it was proximity without transformation, power without submission, religious knowledge without personal reckoning. Bernice carried that family legacy into a Roman future and disappeared from the biblical narrative entirely.",
