      'A young man in Troas who fell asleep during Paul\'s long sermon, tumbled from a third-story window, was taken up dead, and was raised back to life by Paul.',
    bioFull:
      "Eutychus has the most relatable moment in the entire New Testament. Paul was preaching in an upper room in Troas, and he was going long — past midnight, Luke specifies, with many lamps filling the room with heat and flickering light. Eutychus was sitting on the windowsill, probably because the room was packed and the window was where the air was. He sank into a deep sleep, and as Paul \"talked still longer,\" he fell three stories and was picked up dead.\n\nLuke, who was present as an eyewitness (this is one of the \"we\" passages in Acts), is blunt about the outcome: the young man was taken up dead. Not unconscious. Not stunned. Dead. Paul went down, threw himself on the boy — echoing Elijah with the widow's son and Elisha with the Shunammite's boy — and said, \"Do not be alarmed, for his life is in him.\" Then Paul went back upstairs and kept talking until dawn. The congregation was \"not a little comforted,\" which is Luke's understated way of saying they were enormously relieved.\n\nEutychus's name means \"fortunate\" or \"lucky,\" and the irony is layered. He was fortunate, ultimately — not because he avoided death, but because the person whose sermon killed him was also the person equipped to bring him back. His story is often treated as comic relief in Acts, and it is genuinely funny in the way that real life is funny: a kid falls asleep during a long sermon and literally falls out a window. But underneath the humor is a resurrection account — one of the last recorded in Acts — and a reminder that the power present in that cramped upper room was the same power that had been rolling through the narrative since Pentecost.\n\nWhat's most human about the scene is that Paul kept preaching after raising a dead teenager. The congregation ate together, Paul talked until sunrise, and everyone went home. The extraordinary became part of the evening's agenda, sandwiched between the breaking of bread and the morning departure.",
