    bioFull:
      "Epaphras is the church planter who never gets a book of the Bible named after him, even though the church he founded received one of Paul's most theologically dense letters. He brought the gospel to Colossae — and likely to Laodicea and Hierapolis as well — and Paul credits him as a \"faithful minister of Christ\" who taught the Colossians the grace of God in truth. When heresies started creeping into Colossae, Epaphras traveled to Rome to consult Paul in prison, and it was that visit that prompted the letter to the Colossians.\n\nWhat Paul says about Epaphras's prayer life is extraordinary. He describes him as \"always wrestling\" in prayer for the Colossians, using the Greek word agonizomai — the root of \"agonize.\" This wasn't polite devotional time. This was a man who prayed for his people the way athletes competed: with strain, sweat, and everything on the line. Paul certifies that Epaphras worked hard for the churches in Colossae, Laodicea, and Hierapolis — three cities in the Lycus Valley that he apparently felt responsible for simultaneously.\n\nIn Philemon, Paul calls Epaphras his \"fellow prisoner,\" which might mean Epaphras was literally imprisoned alongside Paul or that he voluntarily stayed with Paul in such close solidarity that the term applied. Either way, it suggests Epaphras didn't just visit Paul with a report and leave — he stayed, sharing the confinement, probably continuing to pray for his distant congregations from inside a Roman jail.\n\nEpaphras is the prototype of the pastor who builds something from nothing, loses sleep over the people he served, and gets mentioned in three verses while the church he planted gets a canonical letter. His legacy is the Colossian church itself.",
