    faithJourney:
      "Epaphras's faith was the kind that expressed itself primarily through labor on behalf of other people. He didn't write theology — he built a church. He didn't perform miracles — he prayed until it hurt. Paul's description of him wrestling in prayer uses language from athletic competition, suggesting that Epaphras experienced prayer not as a comfort but as an exertion, a discipline that cost him something physically and emotionally.\n\nWhat's notable is that Epaphras's faith drove him toward dependency, not independence. When his churches faced theological threats he couldn't handle alone, he traveled to Paul. He didn't try to be the sole authority or fight the battle in isolation. His faith was sturdy enough to admit its limits and seek help, which is a maturity that many church founders never reach. He cared more about the church getting the right teaching than about being the one who provided it.",
