    bioFull:
      "Epaphroditus is one of the most tenderly described people in Paul's letters, and his story is a study in the cost of showing up. The church at Philippi — Paul's most generous and beloved congregation — sent Epaphroditus to Rome with financial support for Paul in prison. It was a dangerous journey of over 800 miles, and somewhere along the way or after arrival, Epaphroditus became gravely ill. Paul says he nearly died, and that his illness was connected to \"the work of Christ\" — meaning the mission itself made him sick.\n\nWhat's striking is the emotional texture Paul reveals. Epaphroditus was distressed — not because he was sick, but because the Philippians had heard he was sick, and he was worried about them worrying about him. The man was on his deathbed and his primary concern was that people he loved were upset on his behalf. Paul calls him \"my brother and co-worker and fellow soldier, and your messenger and minister to my need\" — five titles in a single sentence, each one a different facet of what this man meant to Paul and to his church.\n\nPaul sent him back to Philippi with instructions to welcome him with joy and to honor people like him, \"because he nearly died for the work of Christ, risking his life to complete what was lacking in your service to me.\" That phrase — \"risking his life\" — uses a gambling term in Greek, suggesting Epaphroditus rolled the dice with his own survival to carry out the mission. He wasn't a gambler by nature; he was a church member who packed supplies, walked into danger, and almost didn't walk out.\n\nThe letter to the Philippians — one of Paul's warmest and most joyful epistles — was likely carried back to Philippi by Epaphroditus himself. He was the delivery man for one of the most important documents in Christian history, and he delivered it having nearly paid with his life to make the trip possible.",
