    bioBrief:
      'A believer in Thessalonica who hosted Paul and Silas, then was dragged before the city authorities by a mob and forced to post bond for the missionaries\' good behavior.',
    bioFull:
      "Jason opened his door to Paul and Silas, and the consequences arrived within days. The apostles' preaching in the Thessalonian synagogue had provoked a faction of jealous opponents who recruited a street mob, went looking for Paul and Silas at Jason's house, and when they couldn't find the missionaries, dragged Jason himself and some other believers before the city officials. The charge was explosive: \"These men who have turned the world upside down have come here also, and Jason has received them. They are all acting against the decrees of Caesar, saying that there is another king, Jesus.\"\n\nThe accusation was politically brilliant and theologically accidental. The mob framed a religious dispute as sedition against Rome — a charge that no local official could afford to ignore. Jason was suddenly in legal jeopardy not for anything he said or did, but for hosting people who said things that could be interpreted as treasonous. He was collateral damage from someone else's courage, and he absorbed it without, as far as we can tell, blaming Paul or regretting his hospitality.\n\nJason posted bond — a financial guarantee that the missionaries would not cause further trouble — and was released. Paul and Silas left Thessalonica that same night, slipping away to Berea. Jason stayed behind, presumably still liable for the bond, still known to the authorities as the man who housed the troublemakers, still living in the city where the mob knew his address.\n\nHe may be the same Jason mentioned in Romans 16:21 as one of Paul's kinsmen, though this isn't certain. Either way, his contribution to the church was brutally simple: he provided a roof, and it cost him his safety, his money, and his anonymity.",
