    faithJourney:
      "Jason's faith was the kind that expressed itself through a very specific, very costly act: opening his home. Hospitality in the ancient world wasn't just a nice gesture — it was a social contract. By hosting Paul and Silas, Jason publicly associated himself with their message and implicitly guaranteed their conduct. When the mob came, they came to Jason's door because his hospitality had made him legally and socially responsible for his guests.\n\nWhat's striking is that Jason didn't denounce Paul or Silas. He didn't claim ignorance or distance himself from their message. He posted bond from his own resources and absorbed the consequences. His faith wasn't the kind that produced sermons or miracles — it was the kind that produced a spare bed and a willingness to be inconvenienced for someone else's calling. He is the patron saint of people who serve the mission by paying the bills and taking the heat when the mission moves on to the next city.",
