    faithJourney:
      "Crispus's faith required him to walk away from the institution he ran. As synagogue ruler, he wasn't just a member who changed his mind — he was the person responsible for maintaining the very system Paul's message was challenging. His conversion meant simultaneously losing his position, his community standing, and his professional identity. Whatever he heard from Paul, it had to be compelling enough to offset everything he was about to give up.\n\nThe fact that his entire household came with him suggests his faith wasn't a solitary intellectual decision — it reshaped his domestic world as thoroughly as his public one. In the ancient world, a household's conversion meant that everyone under the patriarch's roof — family, servants, dependents — entered a new social and spiritual reality together. Crispus didn't just change his own faith; he redirected the trajectory of every person who lived under his authority. That's a level of conviction that doesn't come from casual interest.",
