    faithJourney:
      "Tertius's faith is visible only in a single sentence, but that sentence tells us everything we need to know about how he understood his relationship to God and to the community. He greeted the Romans \"in the Lord\" — not in his own name, not as Paul's assistant, but as a fellow believer. His faith identity was distinct from his professional function. He was a scribe by trade and a brother by calling, and for one verse, he wanted the Roman church to know that.\n\nThere is something deeply moving about a person whose entire contribution to the most important document they will ever touch is one line of personal connection. Tertius spent hours — possibly days — writing words that weren't his own, arguments he served but didn't author, greetings from people he may or may not have known. And at the end, he asked for one moment to be himself. \"I Tertius, who wrote this letter, greet you in the Lord.\" It's the faith of someone who knows their role is behind the scenes and chooses it willingly, but who also knows they are more than their function — and wants the recipients to know it too.",
