    bioFull:
      "Aristarchus is the man who kept showing up in the worst possible situations and never left. His introduction to the reader is violent: during the silversmith's riot in Ephesus, the mob seized him and his companion Gaius and dragged them into the theater. The crowd was screaming about Artemis, chaos was escalating, and Aristarchus was in the middle of it — not because he had done anything, but because he was with Paul. Being near Paul was, as a vocational hazard, roughly equivalent to being near the epicenter of an earthquake.\n\nHe survived the riot and kept traveling. He appears in the list of companions who accompanied Paul through Macedonia and Greece. He boarded the ship to Rome when Paul, as a prisoner, was transported for his appeal to Caesar. Luke, who was also on that ship, records Aristarchus's presence on a voyage that included a catastrophic storm, a shipwreck on Malta, and weeks of uncertainty about whether anyone would survive. Aristarchus was there for all of it.\n\nIn Colossians, Paul calls him \"my fellow prisoner\" — which either means he was literally imprisoned alongside Paul in Rome or that he had voluntarily restricted his own freedom to serve Paul during his confinement. In Philemon, he sends greetings as one of Paul's co-workers. These brief mentions, spread across multiple books, paint a picture of sustained, unglamorous loyalty over years of shared hardship.\n\nAristarchus never preached a sermon that got recorded. He never wrote a letter. He never performed a miracle. He was grabbed by a mob, sailed through a storm, and sat in a prison — all because he wouldn't leave the side of someone he believed in. His entire recorded legacy is showing up and staying.",
