    faithJourney:
      "Aristarchus's faith was expressed almost entirely through presence. He didn't have a dramatic conversion, a theological crisis, or a moment of divine encounter that Luke recorded. He had a partnership with Paul that he maintained through mob violence, shipwreck, and imprisonment. His faith was the kind that doesn't generate stories about itself — it generates stories about the person it supports. Every account of Paul's later travels and trials implicitly includes Aristarchus standing somewhere nearby, unnamed in the main action but present in the list of companions.\n\nWhat makes his faith distinctive is its durability. Lots of people in Acts had intense, momentary encounters with God — conversions, visions, miraculous deliverances. Aristarchus's faith was a slow-burning commitment that didn't need dramatic fuel to keep going. He was there in Ephesus, there in Macedonia, there on the ship, there in prison. The consistency itself is the testimony. He is proof that faithfulness, over a long enough timeline, becomes its own kind of miracle — not the kind that bends the laws of physics, but the kind that bends the limits of human endurance.",
